Technically a perfect mess with a weak scenario. Gemini with Will Smith did not outrage critics
Dystopian sci-fi spectacle Gemini Man boasts an interesting premise - Will Smith takes on a younger version of himself in the film. But critics say the story is the weakest part of the film. The film will be released in Czech cinemas on 10 October.
Henry Brogan (Will Smith) is the absolute best in his field. He kills efficiently and without unnecessary questions. But one day he decides to hang up his career. Naturally, his employers don't like this, and send another hit man after Henry. The catch is that the assassin is Henry himself, or rather a younger clone of him created from DNA. Can one determined man win a fight against himself? This time, literally.
A sure guarantee of quality should have been three-time Oscar winner Ang Lee. This may be his first sci-fi film, but he has plenty of experience with dramatic action movies, as he demonstrated in the aforementioned Tiger and Dragon and the western Ride with the Devil. Six writers collaborated on the script. The most famous is certainly David Benioff, one of the creators of the highly successful Game of Thrones. But according to the first reviews, even all this was not enough to make a good film.
"While Ang Lee tries to do great things in technical filmmaking, the film itself doesn't have enough character to make it stand out," thinks Screen Daily's Fionnuala Hannigan.
"This underwhelming film is less than the sum of all the talents involved. The weak script and plot are held together only by the filmmakers' technological wizardry," Stephen Dalton of The Hollywood Reporter summed up his opinion.
"Gemini is a case where a huge amount of work has resulted in an incredibly frustrating action film," says Variety reviewer Peter Deburge.
"A confused product born of a bizarre idea," summed up IndieWire's Ella Kemp in her review of the film.
"It's hard to care that one man is a doppelganger of another when neither acts like a human," wrote Nicholas Barber of The Wrap website.
