An unusually open and unique image of Karel Gott in Olga Špátová's feature-length documentary
This unique film by Olga Špátová will premiere in Czech cinemas next spring.
"In mid-September last year, Ivanka and Karel Gott called me and asked me if I would make a documentary about his life with Karel again after ten years. I didn't hesitate a minute! It was and is a great honour for me to film with a man who endured more than half a century in the limelight of Czech culture thanks to his exceptional singing talent, artistic humility and immeasurable diligence. I accepted the challenge to make a feature-length documentary about Karel Gott, whose art has brought joy to three generations of listeners, as a commitment to this legendary singer," says director Olga Špátová.
The first day of filming took place on 22 October last year thanks to a quick arrangement and agreement, and the last shots with Karel Gotts were filmed a few days ago. The goal was and is absolutely clear - to capture authentically Karel Gott as a phenomenal singer who gives himself away to his fans, as a painter, but also as a loving husband and father of his children. A man who for sixty years has been giving joy to several generations with his songs, not only in this country, but also in Europe, and indeed all over the world. A man who has etched himself into the hearts and souls of his listeners by simply being.
The film is not meant to be a showcase of Karel Gott's undisputed fame and achievements. "That's why it's not even possible to compare my previous film, The Gott Phenomenon, with this current one. Each is different. At least in the fact that we filmed them at a different stage in Karel Gott's life, and this is very evident in the personal, almost intimate confession he gave us, which confirmed to all of us what a legend we have the opportunity to work with and spend time with, which is truly indescribable," adds Olga Špátová.
The filmmakers captured Karel Gott during his performances, during meetings with his fans in our country and in Hamburg, but especially in his home environment, whether in Prague, at his cottage in Czech Switzerland, in the village where he spent his childhood, and in other places that played an important role in his life. Thanks to Karel Gott's frank openness, the film will be completely authentic and unique.
"Olga has a great gift for filming with her close-knit team, so that we often let ourselves be carried away by the spontaneous atmosphere and naturally let her into our privacy, which allowed me to talk about quite intimate topics. With my husband, cinematographer Jan Malíř, they actually became part of our family. We originally wanted to release the film in 2019, when I celebrated my anniversary. But since I still had a wonderful summer with my family, I wanted us to film for as long as possible. Well, and since I was all over the place in 2019, my wish was to have it released in theaters next spring. This documentary is a thank you to my fans and everyone who has supported and accompanied me in my profession," says Karel Gott himself about the film.
