XXX Lutz can buy Kiko's competitor, the authorities have allowed. But there's a catch.
"The Office for the Protection of Competition has cleared the merger of the competitors - XLCEE-Holding GmbH on the one hand, and Kika Nábytek and Lambda Properties Czechia on the other - subject to the fulfilment of structural commitments set out in favour of maintaining effective competition," said Martin Švanda, spokesman for the Office for the Protection of Competition.
XLCEE-Holding owns Möbelix stores in addition to the XXX Lutz chain. If it absorbed the Kika chain, it would have too large a share of the Czech furniture and accessories market. Therefore, it has to divest part of the company it is buying.
XLCEE-Holding is also buying Kika branches in other countries where the chain operates, i.e. Hungary, Slovakia and Romania. The antitrust authorities have to approve the transaction there as well. The purchase of 22 foreign branches of Kika from Signa Holding was announced by XXX Lutz in May. Signa took over the bankrupt Kika last year for a symbolic price.
The Kika chain entered the Czech market in 2005 and is the number two after the Swedish company IKEA. Before it was taken over by Austria's Signa, it had been owned by South African firm Steinhoff International Holdings since 2013. The latter faced problems when it discovered irregularities in its accounting. Kika has nine stores in the Czech Republic.
XXX Lutz has been operating in the Czech Republic since 2010. Alongside IKEA, Sconto, Jysk, Asko-Nábytek and Kika, it is one of the largest furniture retailers on the domestic market. The Möbelix brand has the same owner. After taking over Kika's foreign branches, XXX Lutz will already operate over 300 stores in 12 countries. According to the company's website, its annual turnover is EUR 4.4 billion (about CZK 114 billion).
The only ones. Reproduction is not certain, but we don't need to be scared
Some words have unfortunate connotations, even though they only convey the state of affairs. These include the word "only child". It refers to a child growing up without siblings, but it does not sound neutral. "You know, an only child," one says, with nothing to add. Interestingly, this is a trait that "only child" has carried since ancient times, back when terms like "demographic crisis" were not widely used.
Today, even people outside the scientific community know that a fertility rate of 2.1 children per woman is necessary to ensure simple reproduction of the population. It is also widely known that no country in Europe today achieves this figure. At most, France and Sweden come close, but European countries do not have a simple reproduction rate. (Within the West, only Israel stands out with a fertility rate of 3.1 children per woman.) It is a situation made for alarmism. "There are almost as many only children as two-child families," she told LN in an interview. But she left out the devil hidden in the details.
Yes, it is good when the problem is highlighted instead of being downplayed or ideologized. For example, as in Germany, where the campaign for more children can easily be labelled fascist (in the style of "that's what Hitler supported"). It's good to be reminded that many couples are directly planning for only children. It is good if politicians show a willingness to remove the barriers that lead to these decisions (for example, the poor uptake of working from home discourages women from further pregnancies). But despite all this, let's point out one thing.
When Minister Maláčová says that "there are almost as many only children", there is a grain of demagoguery. That statement was made twenty years ago. Let us recall that the last time the fertility rate in the Czech Republic ensured simple reproduction was in 1980 ("Husák's children"). Then it declined to an appalling 1.14 in 2000. But since then it has risen by almost 50 per cent, to the current 1.70 children per woman, which is above the European average. This is still not enough for simple reproduction, so politicians need to be active. They can only tone down the alarmism a little.
Berlin is responding to public pressure and tackling the housing crisis. It will buy 6,000 apartments from a private company
Berlin will buy 6,000 former social housing units that the city sold 15 years ago from a private Luxembourg firm, ADO Properties SA, for 920 million euros (CZK 23.8 billion). The move comes in response to public pressure, which is rebelling against skyrocketing rent prices. Berlin Senator Katrin Lompscher of the Left Party (Die Linke) said it was the biggest such buyout in the history of the German capital. The opposition has criticised the move.
"The intention is to keep rents stable in Berlin and to give tenants security," Berlin Mayor Michael Müller (SPD) said in a statement. The municipal firm Gewobag will take over the thousands of apartments located in the Spandau and Reinickendorf districts in the western part of the city this December.
According to Jefferies analyst Thomas Rothäusler, the city bought too expensively. Rothäusler told Bloomberg that he estimates that it overpaid for the units by about 10 percent above their book value.
The German opposition Liberal Party (FDP) says the Berlin authorities are contributing to real estate speculation by their actions. The FDP said this in a tweet on Friday. The Alternative for Germany (AfD) protest party called the move a "waste of money".
Already in mid-July, the Gewobag took back 670 apartments in Berlin's Karl-Marx-Allee, the weekly Der Spiegel recalled on its website. The council did not disclose the price at the time. The dispute over the flats on the former GDR-era exhibition street was accompanied by protests and filled the front pages of the German press. It has become a symbol of the plight of tenants in major German cities, the paper said.
The German capital used to be famous for its low cost of living and low rents. In recent years, however, it has become more attractive. Rental prices have doubled in the past decade, according to AFP, making it difficult for some residents to find affordable housing.
