Prague Stock Exchange rose slightly, Czech banks, O2 and Avast did well
The Prague Stock Exchange closed the trading week with a slight growth. The PX index rose by 0.13 per cent to 1038.45 points. It was driven up by Czech banks, telecommunications company O2 and technology firm Avast. On the other hand, Austrian titles and media company CME did not fare well. This is according to the results of trading on the stock exchange website.
For most of Friday's session, the Prague Stock Exchange traded in slightly positive territory and eventually ended with a small profit. "However, it (the PX index) lost slightly over one percent for the whole week," noted Josef Dudek of Fio banka.
Domestic banks partially corrected the declines of the past few days. Komerční banka improved 0.82 percent to 803 koruna and Moneta Money Bank 0.41 percent to 72.80 koruna. Shares in Avast rose 0.89 percent to 113 koruna and operator O2 gained 0.46 percent to 216.50 koruna.
Kofola's securities rose the most, up 1.38 percent to 294 koruna. Tobacco company Philip Morris gained less than a percent, with its shares rising to 13,640 crowns.
The securities of energy firm CEZ stagnated at Thursday's value of 520 crowns.
Three titles were losers - Erste Bank wrote off 0.87 percent to 779.20 crowns, CME 0.73 percent to 109 crowns and insurer VIG 0.40 percent to 618 crowns.
The crown weakened slightly against both major world currencies. It lost four cents against the euro to 25.85 koruna/euro, and three cents against the dollar to 23.62 koruna/USD. It follows from data on the Patria Online server.
