The Attorney General has reinstated the prosecution of a mother who manipulated her daughter against her father
Supreme State Prosecutor Pavel Zeman disagrees with the acquittal of a mother who manipulated her daughter and disrupted her relationship with her father over a long period of time. She was facing charges of abuse and endangering her upbringing. The regional court acquitted her, but Zeman disagrees. His appeal to the Supreme Court suggests that such conduct may constitute a criminal offence.
The Supreme Court's decision could have wider implications for other cases. "A more specific definition of such a specific form of abuse can be considered necessary also in terms of guiding further application practice," Zeman's appeal states.
Last year, the district court in Svitavy initially found the woman guilty of both abuse of a ward and endangering the upbringing of a child. She had formed a strong, almost symbiotic bond with her daughter, even when she was supposed to be entrusted to her father.
The result was a pathological fixation on the mother and a markedly negative relationship with the father. The situation marked the emotional development of the daughter, who was even hospitalised. She had threatened to harm herself if she was handed over to her father's care.
The Svitavy court sentenced the mother to two years' imprisonment with a two-year suspended sentence. However, the Pardubice branch of the regional court acquitted the woman on appeal, saying it was not a criminal offence. The regional court repeated the same verdict after the Supreme Court ordered it to decide again.
The Regional Court stated that situations where one parent manipulates a child against the other are by no means exceptional. They are dealt with in custody proceedings, possibly with the help of psychologists or youth welfare authorities. Only rarely is criminal law the solution.
However, according to the Attorney General, the woman had committed both abuse and endangering the child's upbringing. "The accused acted quite purposefully in arousing negative feelings in her daughter towards her father, and purposefully reinforced those negative emotions. In doing so, she not only pursued the unlawful intention to restrict or exclude the father's contact with the minor, but she must necessarily have been aware that this would have negative consequences in the minor's psychosocial sphere," the appeal states.
Zeman asked the Supreme Court to send the case back to the regional court once more. The appeal states that the child is now in the custody of the father.
