The renovation of the Krkonoše Museum will be a year late
The administration of the Krkonoše National Park (KRNAP) has postponed the deadline for submitting bids for the second tender for the repair of the Krkonoše Museum in Vrchlabí by three weeks. The original deadline for opening the envelopes was 20 September, said Radek Drahný, spokesman for the national park. The reason for the postponement of the deadline for submitting bids is a reduction in the budget from CZK 110 million to CZK 83 million.
"We are currently working with prices that are on the market. There has been a change in the budget, it is the price we expect to be offered. If someone submits a bid that is acceptable, the work will start as soon as possible," Drahný said.
Compared to the original plans, the start of the museum's renovation is about a year late. KRNAP wanted to have a contractor selected for the construction part by the end of last year and to start work this spring. According to the national park administration, the CZK 123 million in European funding for the project is not in jeopardy.
The KRNAP administration has not been able to select a construction company for the museum repairs. It launched a second tender this summer because in the previous tender all the bids from companies significantly exceeded the then estimated price of CZK 65 million. The bids exceeded CZK 100 million.
The museum, which is housed in a former Augustinian monastery and belongs to the KRNAP Administration, has been closed since autumn 2017. The selected company should provide the construction part of the project. The total cost, including the construction of the new exhibition, is estimated at CZK 210 million. After the transformation of the expositions, a KRNAP visitor centre should be established in the now vacated building by the end of 2021.
The renovated museum with a new interactive exposition, which should be a story of nature and people settled in the mountains and build on the successful Stone and Life exposition, should serve as a representative gateway to the Krkonoše Mountains for visitors. The visitor centre should provide information about the past and present of the Giant Mountains in the most comprehensible way and motivate people to explore and protect the mountains. It should also take on the role of a traditional museum. The centre will also offer opportunities to organise concerts, festivals, theatre performances or lectures in the open air. There are plans to build a new entrance to the building, a research room or a café.
