Kovosvit exports about half of its production. Its standard markets are the EU and Russia, and to a lesser extent Asia last year. This year, Kuchař counts India among the most interesting, where Kovosvit won an order for machines enabling five-axis machining worth CZK 100 million. This year, the company also exported two five-axis machines worth CZK 30 million to China. "Another order in the same volume has been negotiated, which we would like to fulfil before the end of the year," Kuchař said. Kovosvit is facing restrictions on the Russian market and elsewhere due to sanctions.
Last year, the company sold two five-axis machining centres to France, a company that is a subcontractor to Airbus. It delivered another machine to it in May this year and is expected to deliver one more at the end of the year or in early 2020.
The company's main investment this year was a CZK 20 million switch from steam to hot water heating. Kovosvit employs 500 people and the average worker's wage is CZK 28,500. The company is looking for casting grinders for the foundry, machinists, turners and electricians.
The company has been owned by industrialist and armourer Jaroslav Strnad since September 2016. The company has a tradition in the production of machine tools. It was founded in 1939 by Tomáš Bat'a. The company had up to three thousand employees at the time.
