There are up to 60 times fewer insects than 40 years ago
No other animal class is more abundant in nature than insects. Beetles, butterflies and other species make up more than half of life on Earth. But there are increasing reports that the insect kingdom is shrinking radically. Another scientific study on the subject came out just this week, and it says the situation is even more serious than humanity has realised.
The study is based on field research in the tropical rainforest of Puerto Rico, in which American scientists replicated a similar survey from 1976. As they write right at the beginning of the report, there are "ten to sixty times fewer insects in the rainforest today." This is a decline in the entire population, not in the number of species, and the survey covered all arthropods, not just insects. Because of the insect die-off, the population of other fauna that depend on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs and lizards, is also declining.
The authors of the research link their findings directly to climate change. According to them, the average air temperature in the rainforest has risen by two degrees Celsius over the past thirty years, and warming has become a driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. The study thus shows that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously thought, according to the authors.
The report was the subject of a major story in the Washington Post on Monday, which gave the new findings a hyper-alarming headline. "It's one of the most disturbing articles I've ever read," entomologist David Wagner of the University of Connecticut, whom the paper quotes as an independent expert, told the paper.
The insect die-off is also affecting Europe. "In our country, the decline is also of the order of magnitude," points out Lukáš Čížek of the Institute of Entomology of the Academy of Sciences. However, he says that in addition to climate change, it is also necessary to take into account the changes in the landscape, which play a significant role in Europe. "In our country, it has just been running for a significantly longer period of time than in Puerto Rico," Čížek adds to explain why scientists could measure such a rapid decline in the rainforest compared to the 1970s.
Nokia sues Brno firm over Lokia name. People won't confuse us, Moravians believe
Nokia has filed an opposition to the Lokia trademark application with the Industrial Property Office. However, according to CCV, confusion of products is unlikely.
Brno-based software development firm CCV is facing legal action from Finnish telecommunications equipment manufacturer Nokia. The Finns do not like the fact that the Brno firm's warehouse management software is called Lokia WMS, the E15 daily reported. Nokia has therefore filed objections against the Lokia trademark application with the Industrial Property Office. CCV believes that confusion is unlikely.
Marketing director Petr Ondrasek said that two dozen customers are already using the programme, which has been on the market since last September.
"The Nokia brand enjoys recognition and trust around the world. When someone tries to register a trademark that we believe may lead to confusion or dilution of our brand, we take action to protect our valuable asset," said Nokia spokesman Mark Durrant.
The Brno-based developers say they did not have the brand, famous in the past for its mobile phones, in mind when creating the stock programme. According to CCV, the name Lokia is based on the Latin name for a species of dragonfly whose rapid movement is meant to be analogous to the movement of warehouse workers through a warehouse.
"In the Czech market, the possibility of confusion is unlikely. We sell modern cloud software that companies use to equip their warehouse operations, and we are not really targeting the mobile phone manufacturing sector. And we don't want to be compared to a brand that may be missing the train in its field," CCV manager Tomáš Kormaňák told E15.
CCV applied for brand protection with the Industrial Property Office in August before the program was launched. "It applied for protection for goods and services belonging to classes 9, 35 and 42, as software belongs to class 9, related business management services in warehouses belong to class 35 and computer software development belongs to class 42 according to the international classification," Ondrášek said.
Nokia's opposition is based on the fact that Nokia's earlier trademark is valid in all classes of goods and services and thus covers the widest possible range of goods and services, and thus naturally overlaps also in classes 9, 35 and 42. "The CCV does not dispute the opponent's claim as far as the coincidence on these classes of products and services is concerned. However, in reality they are completely different marks aimed at different target groups," Ondrášek said.
According to E15, brand disputes can take months and can complicate a company's operations.
