There was a fire in the underground of the CSA mine in Karviná, no one was injured
There was a fire in the underground of the CSA mine in Karviná this morning. The cause of the fire is not yet known. However, no one was injured, the mining company's spokesman Ivo Čelechovský told ČTK.
The fire broke out at 04:25 in the tunnel at a depth of about 1,200 metres. "None of the employees were hurt, no one was injured. Bánsk rescuers immediately intervened at the site and eliminated the fire by direct intervention and also carried out a survey of the area. The workplace was immediately closed and made inaccessible," the spokesman said. The exact cause of the fire will now be investigated by a special commission.
In the former Ostrava-Karviná district, coal is mined only in the Karviná part, in the mines of ČSA, Lazy, Darkov, ČSM-North and ČSM-South. Mining at the Lazy Mine is expected to end this year, while the other mines are also expected to gradually decline. OKD is the only producer of hard coal in the Czech Republic, with last year's production of 4.62 million tonnes. About 9,000 people work in the mines.
