Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to see if it can hold cryptocurrencies. It's responding to a directive from state-owned Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which is seeking to be able to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank and then have the bank pay the oil firm's suppliers in cryptocurrencies. The staff is also studying a proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies against foreign exchange reserves, which are now near a 30-year low. Citing information from four sources, Bloomberg reported.
Sanctions imposed by the United States on President Nicolás Maduro's authoritarian regime have largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system. This has exacerbated the economic crisis in the country. Meanwhile, the current crisis is one of the most serious in global comparison, which has forced officials to use a mixture of different methods to move money around. While Maduro's efforts to launch the world's first state-owned cryptocurrency have failed, the ongoing efforts to use digital currencies show how desperate the government is to find ways around the restrictions.
Neither the Venezuelan central bank nor PDVSA responded to a request for comment.
It is not clear how PDVSA came to own bitcoins and ether, nor how much value it holds in these currencies. The company has struggled to get payments from customers through conventional channels because large banks are unwilling to do business with sanctioned entities. Last month, the company received most of a $700 million (16.6 billion) payment in Chinese yuan because the parties were unable to find financial institutions to facilitate the transaction.
PDVSA may be reluctant to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market because it would require it to register with the exchange and undergo due diligence, so-called due diligence. Instead, it wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank to pay the entities to which PDVSA owes money. Oil company officials believe that the central bank is less exposed to potential obstacles that could arise when paying with cryptocurrency.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized internet ledger known as a blockchain to verify and record transactions. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are enabled without the need for an intermediary. Few banks are engaging in digital currencies because of the money laundering and customer information issues that come with them and complicate compliance.
Cryptocurrencies are experiencing a comeback this year after the debacle of 2018 due to expectations of greater adoption by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain volatile. Bitcoin is down nearly 20 percent in the last four days, but has gained about 130 percent since the beginning of the year.
