1.1 The purpose of the Project Charter is to define the formal management processes and communication arrangements between the Parties for the purpose of fulfilling the object of the Contract so that the performance of the Work or provision of the Services is in accordance with the Contract and this Project Management Methodology. The Project Charter shall make available to those persons involved in the execution of the Work or the provision of the Services those parts of the Contract that are necessary for the fulfilment of its object. The Project Charter shall specify the composition of the project's organisational structure, the method of communication, the control and escalation mechanisms and the structure of the project portal where all documentation related to the execution of the work or the provision of services shall be archived. The Project Charter shall be drafted by the Project Leads and approved by the Steering Committee at its initial meeting.
2. Organisational structure of the project
2.1 The organizational components of the Project are (1) the Project Steering Committee ("SCP") and (2) the Project Management Team ("PMT") and (3) the Work Teams. The SCP and the PVP are the permanent organizational units of the Project. Work Teams are temporary organizational units of the Project.
Steering Committee
3.1 Powers of the SCP / Steering Committee of the project in particular:
3.1.1 approve the Project Charter; and
3.1.2 resolve escalated issues that have not been resolved at the SCP level; and
3.1.3 resolve issues affecting the scope of work to be performed or services to be provided; and
3.1.4 address issues related to the delivery schedule; and
3.1.5 address issues related to the remuneration or fee structure for the services or work performed; and
3.1.6 accept individual deliveries, services, parts of the work and/or the work as a whole; and
3.2 Members of the SCP / On behalf of the Client, the members of the SCP shall be (1) the Project Sponsor for the Business and (2) the ISIT Division Director and (3) the Project Manager. For the Contractor, the SCP members are (1) the Management Representative and (2) the Project Manager.
3.3 The SCP/SCP shall meet at least quarterly.  The exact days on which the SCP meets regularly shall be determined by the Project Manager in the Project Charter. The SCP shall meet whenever a significant delivery schedule milestone is evaluated (e.g., start or completion of the acceptance procedure). The SCP shall meet whenever a Project Manager calls for a SCP meeting. The SCP shall meet at the Client's headquarters.
3.4 The SCP meeting agenda / SCP meeting agenda and the papers to be discussed shall be delivered to the SCP members by the Project Manager for the Contractor at least 3 working days prior to the SCP meeting. The SCP meeting shall always discuss the project status report and draft minutes related to the acceptance of the deliverables, services or work.
3.5 Right to Invite Experts and Consultants / If either party deems it necessary, it shall have the right to invite experts or consultants to the SCP meeting, but shall notify the other party in advance, stating the reasons why the presence of experts or consultants at the SCP meeting is advisable.
3.6 Voting / After discussion of each agenda item, SCP members shall vote on the motion that is put forward for that agenda item. Each SCP member shall have one vote.
3.7 SCP Decision Affecting the Contract Terms / If the SCP decision affects the contract terms under which the Work is performed or the Services are provided, in particular if the SCP decision affects the remuneration for which the Work is performed or the Services are provided, the Client shall, without undue delay after such decision is taken, prepare an amendment to the subject contract.
3.8 Minutes / Minutes of the SCP meeting shall be prepared by the Project Manager for the Client and delivered to the Project Manager for the Contractor.
4. Project Management
4.1 Powers of the SCP / The project management of the project shall in particular:
4.1.1 control all deliverables of the various phases of the execution of the Work or provision of the Services; and
4.1.2 evaluate and refine the schedule of deliverables and progress of the Work in the performance of the Work or provision of the Services; and
4.1.3 discuss changes that do not affect the wording of the Contract; and
4.1.4 manage the interaction between the Client and the Contractor; and
4.1.5 manage the risks and remedial actions associated with the performance of the Work or the provision of the Services; and
4.1.6 escalates to the SCP meeting.
4.2 Members of the SCP / On behalf of the Client, the members of the SCP shall be (1) the Project Manager and (2) the Principal Business Analyst and (3) the Application Architect. For the Contractor, the members of the PVP are (1) the Project Manager and (2) the Principal Business Analyst and (3) the Principal Architect.
4.3 The SCP / PVP shall meet weekly, at the Client's site or by remote communication.
4.4 The SCP meeting agenda and supporting documents / The SCP meeting agenda and supporting documents to be discussed shall be delivered to the SCP members by the Project Manager for the Contractor at least 1 working day prior to the SCP meeting.  The PVP shall always discuss at its meeting:
4.4.1 the implementation of open tasks from previous PVPs; and
4.4.2 the progress of the execution of the Work or the provision of the Services; and
4.4.3 the execution and update of the schedule of works; and
4.4.4 the problems identified and how they will be resolved; and
4.4.5 a plan for further action; and
4.4.6 the risks associated with the execution of the work or provision of the services; and
4.4.7 evaluation and other requirements for the Client's cooperation; and
4.4.8 the status and severity of unresolved defects or incidents; and
4.4.9 change requests; and
4.5 Right to Invite Experts and Consultants / If their presence is expedient for the effective conduct of the meeting, both parties shall have the right to invite experts and consultants or members of the project teams to the PVP meeting.
4.6 Minutes / Minutes of the PVP meeting shall be prepared by the Project Manager for the Client and delivered to the Project Manager for the Contractor.
5. Working teams
5.1 Work Teams / Work Teams shall consist of personnel of the Client or Contractor and third party personnel as appropriate.  In particular, the Work Teams shall (1) perform specific parts of the Work or Services and (2) provide the know-how necessary for the performance of the Work or the provision of the Services and (3) provide factual and technical support for further decision-making.
5.2 Roles in work teams / The occupation of roles shall always be adapted to the current stage of the execution of the work or provision of services. On the Customer's side, the members of the work team shall consist of:
5.2.1 Business analysts of the subject area(s)
5.2.2 Guarantor / key user of the subject area(s)
5.2.3 Technical and technological infrastructure specialist
On the Contractor's side, the members of the working team are:
5.2.4 Principal consultant/analyst - architect of the proposed solution
5.2.5 Consultant/analyst
5.2.6 Technical Infrastructure Specialist
5.2.7 Developer
5.2.8 Tester, trainer
5.2.9 Operations and Installation Specialist
6. A full list of the individual project roles and their communication matrix is specified in the Project Charter.
6.1 Communication management / Communication in the project is mainly managed by the project leader. Communication is always conducted in a substantive manner with the aim of resolving individual tasks as quickly and efficiently as possible. Mutual, managed, communication between project teams includes in particular:
6.1.1 Project meetings (SCP, PVP, consultations, workshops, ...)
6.1.2 Acceptance and handover procedures
6.1.3 Transmission and storage of tasks, information and documents
6.1.4 Recording of change requests
6.1.5 Recording of defects and incidents
6.2 Project meetings - agenda and supporting documents / The schedule and task list from project meetings is always updated at the next meeting. Handouts to be covered in the project meeting will be sent by the project leaders to the meeting participants in advance according to the subject of the meeting. The documents shall be registered and updated on the project portal.
6.3 Minutes of Project Meetings / The Client's Project Manager shall prepare written minutes of each Project Meeting and deliver them to the Contractor's Project Manager on the next working day after the Project Meeting.
6.4 Modifications and additions to the minutes of the project meeting / Modifications and additions to the minutes of the project meeting shall be made by the participants within 2 working days from the date of receipt of the minutes. The Project Manager shall chair the discussion on the modifications and additions to the minutes. Modifications and additions to the minutes are not a venue for discussion. After incorporation of the modifications and additions, the Client's Project Manager shall close the project meeting minutes and store them on the project portal. The deadline for comments on the project meeting minutes may be changed by the Project Manager by agreement. If any period for comment on the minutes of the project meeting expires without comments from the meeting participants, the minutes shall be deemed approved.
7. Risk management
7.1 Identification and recording of risks / In the course of the execution of the work or provision of the services, all persons involved shall identify and subsequently manage in a documented manner risks that may affect the quality of the deliverables or the deadlines for the execution of the work or provision of the services. Risks shall be recorded by the Project Manager on the project portal, including their severity.
7.2 Discussion of risks at the PVP meeting / Discussion and evaluation of risks is a mandatory agenda item at each PVP meeting. The PVP meeting shall determine measures to eliminate or minimise risks.
7.3 Escalation / If there is disagreement or if a risk is identified with severity affecting the contractual arrangements or schedule or remuneration, such risk shall be escalated by the PVP to the SCP meeting.
8. Quality Management
8.1 The basic tool for managing the quality of project deliverables is the acceptance procedure. The subject of quality assurance is:
8.1.1 Checking the completeness of the subject matter of the work or the provision of services so as to fulfil the purpose of the contract
8.1.2 Evaluating and resolving comments, defects and incidents to fulfil the purpose of the contract
8.1.3 Checking that the documentation is up to date and complete
8.1.4 Checking that the delivery schedule is adhered to
8.1.5 Implement approved changes
8.1.6 Results of other agreed activities as per meeting minutes.
