Annex 7 / Incident Classification
The items below are for inspiration only.  This annex must be accurately and comprehensively worded by the Project Manager.
Incidents from the operational environment
Incident Category A means Incident in the operational environment if for example:
the user is unable to log into the Application
the Application repeatedly crashes at the same step and the user cannot complete a critical process
When the system exhibits excessive timeouts (twice the defined performance parameters)
responses to user activity
when it is not possible to print documentation or a report for a client
when incorrect data is displayed to the end customer
Critical Application functionality/processes are:
account creation or cancellation
running daily statements
Category B Incident means Incident in the operational environment if for example:
the user's work is slowed down, but this does not have a serious impact on workflow adherence
non-critical functionality is unavailable to the end user.
Incident category C means Incident in the operational environment if for example:
a language defect or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphical error in the user interface that confuses the user in the use of the interface
if it is a Documentation defect
Acceptance environment incidents
Incident category TA means Acceptance Environment Incident if for example:
a client cannot be established in the system
Incident category TB means Acceptance Environment Incident if for example:
It is not possible to change any parameter of the client's account
Incident category TC means Incident in the acceptance environment if for example:
A language defect or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphical error in the user interface that confuses the user in the use of the interface
if it is a Documentation defect
