Sabre combines a conventional aircraft engine with a rocket engine. It's designed to propel the aircraft at twice the speed of Concorde. "When the Sabre engine is operational, it could allow us to fly to Australia in about four hours," Turnock said. And the distance between London and New York, for example, could be covered in one hour.
The Independent notes that so-called hypersonic flights, in which five times the speed of sound is exceeded, are complicated by engine overheating. But Sabre (Synergetic Air Breathing Rocket Engine) should deal with this problem by using super-cold helium to prevent temperatures from rising.
"The most important thing about Sabre is that it is a hybrid of a rocket and aircraft engine, powered by a stream of exhaust gases generated from the air," says Shaun Driscoll of Reaction Engines. "Rockets have not evolved that much in the last 70 years, whereas aircraft ones have. So if you combine the engines, you can have a very lightweight and efficient propulsion system and essentially create a space plane," he added.
The engine is currently being tested, with test flights expected to begin around the middle of next year. Commercial flights will then begin around 2030.
