The traditionally high-profile battle for the fastest man on the planet will be a hunt for defending silver medallist Christian Coleman at the World Championships. The 23-year-old American leads the world charts with a time of 9.81 seconds and has lost only once this year. But his start at the top of the season has been jeopardised by a case of missed doping tests.
The U.S. Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) closed his case in early September without filing charges on a technicality. Coleman did fail three doping tests last year and this year, but not in the space of 12 months. Indeed, his first offence was backdated by the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) to April 1, 2018, the start of the second quarter, but he did not miss the actual test until June 6. And because the third omission occurred on April 29, 2019, Coleman committed the misconduct of three failed controls in 12 months.
Coleman's defense was that he merely forgot to update the athletes' whereabouts on the app. "I don't do drugs or take anything legal. A lot of athletes take legal creatine or protein powder or various other supplements for faster recovery. And I don't take anything, I work hard and that's what it's all about," he said before the start of the World Championships.
He suffered his only defeat in six 100-miler starts this year right at the start of the season at the Shanghai Diamond League, where he was beaten by compatriot Noah Lyles by just six thousandths of a second. He took advantage of Coleman's absence to triumph in the Diamond League final, but will only run the 200 at the World Championships.
Twenty-two-year-old Nigerian Divine Oduduru is the second fastest on paper with a 9.86, but he has only been successful in American university competitions.
Thirty-seven-year-old American Justin Gatlin, who shone at Stanford in June with a 9.87, will defend his title. But he ran only 10.29 in his last 100 in Zagreb because he slightly injured his back thigh muscle.
South Africa's Akani Simbine, triple Olympic medallist from Rio Andre de Grasse and European champion Zharnel Hughes are also among the favourites. The fastest Jamaican is 2011 world champion Yohan Blake with a time of 9.96.
