His epilepsy has complicated his love of sport, but thanks to surgery he has new hope
The first time Honzik's parents noticed something was wrong with him was when he was a year and a half old. He would always stare into space for a few minutes, become immobile and not respond to anyone. The paediatrician therefore sent him to the paediatric neurology clinic where, after a series of examinations, the doctors diagnosed him with epilepsy and immediately put him on medication, but it did not work immediately.
It took almost a year for the doctors to find the ideal combination of medications that stopped his seizures altogether. So at the age of five, the doctors took him off the medication, and because the seizures did not return, his parents assumed that Honza was healthy and started to encourage him to play more sports. He cycled, skied, played tennis and floorball, and spent his free time playing games with his sister and friends. But at the age of eleven he had another seizure and everything started all over again.
The doctors tried different combinations of drugs again, but this time nothing worked, and the seizures in the form of absences kept recurring. Since Honza always stopped perceiving during a seizure, his parents were terrified that he would get it during sports and get hurt. Gradually, Honza stopped cycling and replaced downhill skis with cross-country skis and a snowboard. Although the sport gave him a seizure from time to time, he never gave it up completely. He even fulfilled his dream and finished the Spartan Race, but together with a friend who was always on the lookout to help him in case of an emergency.
When Honz was 15 years old, his parents decided to try a change of doctor and turned to the specialists at the Motol Hospital. After a series of examinations, the doctors there decided that Honza was a candidate for surgery to remove the lesion - the source of his epileptic seizures - from his brain. "I had to undergo 2 operations in a row, first the doctors inserted probes into my brain, which sensed its activity, then only they could remove the deposit. It was hell for me for several weeks. I had to lie down and hardly move, wires were sticking out of my head, which were connected to the computer," recalls Honza.
The operation was successful and the doctors removed the rather large lesion. "The first days after the operation were very mentally difficult, Honza was apathetic, confused, sad and hardly spoke. Compared to how lively and communicative he normally is, it was a frightening change, but fortunately after a few days everything returned to normal," says the mother, adding: "A month and a half after the operation he had 1 seizure, but according to the doctors it happens. He has been seizure free for 3 months since then."
This school year, Honza will graduate, besides sports he enjoys languages and has started working with the E Society, with whom he travels to schools to give talks about epilepsy. Honza is not yet fully engaged in sports activities, he is starting to return to sports slowly. "I'm learning how to do sports properly, how to breathe well so that I don't put my body under sudden stress, which is quite a challenge with my competitive nature," explains Honza.
This year, he will therefore not yet be actively participating in the traditional EPPI paddling triathlon, which brings together epilepsy patients and healthy athletes and which will take place this weekend on 28 September 2019 at the Veselská sandpit. But hopefully next year it will be.
