Renowned French chef Marc Veyrat lost his third Michelin star this January, a year after he won it. He plans to sue the publisher of the red guide to receive the exact reasons for the demotion. Veyrat also questions the competence of the Michelin inspectors, who he says mistook saffron for cheddar. The first trial is due to take place in November.
The chef of the famous restaurant La Maison de Bois in the Alpine region of Haute Savoie lost one of his three Michelin stars in January this year. He will be taking the publisher of the prestigious Le Guide Michelin to court because he believes the commissioners' conclusion was not properly justified. In addition, he said, the withdrawal of the star had taken place without any notice. "I have been suffering from depression for six months. How dare you mess with the health of the chefs?" Veyrat told the commissioners.
Michelin reportedly gave the chef only vague reasons, such as that the chef had put cheddar in the soufflé, which the inspectors did not like. "I put saffron in it and the gentlemen thought it was cheddar because it was yellow. I've been lovingly working with Savoyard ingredients since the beginning," Veyrat objected to the decision. He is convinced of the strong incompetence of the Michelin commissioners: "You are frauds who are just stirring up controversy for commercial reasons." An outraged Veyrat does not understand "how they could dare to say that we put cheddar in our soufflé". "They insulted our region, my staff were mad about it. We have eggs from our own chickens, milk from our own cows, gardeners pick fresh herbs every morning," he fumed.
The distinctive chef, always wearing a black hat and dark glasses, is an opponent of the new generation of Michelin commissioners and is calling for his restaurant to be removed from the red guide. But the publisher refuses. "As long as the business remains open and our inspectors select it again, we will continue to recommend it," says Gwendal Poullennec, Michelin's international director.
According to Michelin, the chef's lawsuit shows that he has no meaningful charge yet and his lawyer has yet to help him formulate one. "We regret Mr Veyrat's rude communication with us. But we will examine his comments carefully," he said.
In addition to La Maison de Bois, Marc Veyart owns two other three-star restaurants.
