Germany on Friday reported the first case of a person contracting West Nile fever on German territory after being bitten by an infected mosquito. DPA news agency reported. So far, all the patients have contracted the virus while travelling or through contact with sick animals. Experts say the groundbreaking case of infection is linked to climate change.
The Robert Koch Institute said a 70-year-old man from Saxony had contracted the virus. He had a severe illness and was treated for brain inflammation at a hospital in Leipzig. He is now well.
The West Nile virus was first detected in 1937 in Uganda. It has since spread to large parts of Africa, Asia and Europe and, in the 1990s, to the United States. It is carried mainly by birds and also by mosquitoes that become infected with their infected blood.
