The hip or the hip?
On the face of it, it's nothing complicated.
Most nouns in Czech express only one grammatical gender, so it's no problem to determine whether they are masculine, feminine or neuter.
But then there is also a fairly large group of nouns whose gender is not fixed.
Such nouns fluctuate between two genders.
When inflected, they take on double endings and in some cases remain in their uncloned form.
For example, the words "svízel" or "hip" are both masculine and feminine, the former inflected according to the pattern "machine", the latter according to the pattern "song".
Another group of nouns have different forms in the first singular case, for example, "row/row", "kedluben/kedlubna" or "potato/potato" (meaning food).
Both forms are spelled the same way, have the same meaning, and are therefore freely interchangeable.
Some expressions may differ regionally, for example "okurka" in Bohemia and "okurek" in Moravia, but in this case the Moravian variant is ungrammatical, as are other Czech-Moravian word pairs: "příkop" and "příkopa", "kobliha" and "koblih", etc.
Some of the words that have entered Czech from other languages were originally non-cloned, but gradually they are adopting Czech endings.
A typical example is the word 'image', which is both masculine and feminine, or the word 'bufet', which has remained uncloned in the middle gender but has masculine endings like 'hrad'.
Civilization in the borrowed tense
Recently I remembered a beautiful "line" from one of the great stories by Simek and Grossmann, set partly in a cemetery, which goes like this: "I pointed out to her that she was crying all right, but on someone else's grave!" It occurred to me that many of the world's politicians engaged in the senseless fight against climate change are now behaving very similarly.
They behave as if humans ruled planet Earth. In reality, we are but a speck on its surface, which it can blow away with its enormous forces like a gust of wind blowing out a candle flame. Probably few of them watch the famous British and American science documentaries about the destructive powers of our blue marble. After all, all it would take is for one of the larger active volcanoes to get a good "fart" and our advanced civilization would go down in flames.
And that this is highly likely to happen in the near future. A number of large volcanoes have, in the opinion of leading volcanologists, become "charged and armed" (Katla in Iceland, for example).
In a way, it would be ideal if the eruption, if it must happen one day, were to happen as soon as possible. Before trillions of dollars are wasted on measures to reduce the production of carbon dioxide, because any properly angry volcano, together with dust and poisonous volcanic gases, can release at least a hundred times more of it into the air than has been saved at the expense of the people of Europe.
It therefore makes no sense to forcibly limit CO2 production. Moreover, it has been scientifically proven that, with a significantly higher proportion of CO2 in the air, plants produce more biological matter and are also more resistant to drought. For humanity, any warming is much more favourable than, for example, a rapid return of the ice age.
If we take into account the as yet understudied influence of solar cycles on the Earth's climate, we have only one reasonable conclusion: let us try hard to keep the Earth as clean as possible, and let us try to adapt to other changes with which we cannot compare in strength at the lowest possible cost.
