Everything you know about obesity is wrong, proclaims the headline of a lengthy text written for the Huffington Post by Michael Hobbes and photographed by Finlay Mackay. The provocative afterword then goes on to say that for decades the medical community has ignored the facts about obesity and waged a fierce (and also unnecessary) war on overweight people that has not only tainted public opinion but also ruined many lives. But now it is time for a new paradigm.
What Hobbes states right at the outset is that there is often a very long and tedious road from knowing and understanding the facts to putting them into practice. He mentions the case of scurvy, where some captains as early as the seventeenth century gave lemons, limes and oranges to their crew in the belief that they would prevent disease. However, the British navy abandoned this practice because of fears about increased costs. The clear effect of fruit in preventing and treating disease was then demonstrated in the mid-18th century, but it took another fifty years for the navy to take note. Even seat belts existed long before the invention of the automobile, but only became compulsory in the 1960s, just as the first confirmed asbestos-related death dates from 1906, yet its first ban came in 1973.
"Every public health discovery - no matter how significant - has always had to compete with traditions, prejudices, and financial incentives within the society in which it was to be implemented," Hobbes writes. In American society today, nearly 80 percent of the adult population and about one-third of children meet the definition of overweight or obese. More Americans are now living with obesity than with breast cancer, Alzheimer's, Parkinson's and HIV combined.
Yet obesity is seen as a uniquely personal failing of the individual, which is said to burden the health care system and reduce GDP. The fear of fatness is so great in the population that Americans now spend more money on diets than they spend on computer games and movies. But the truth is that diets don't work. As early as 1959, research showed that 95 to 98 percent of attempts to lose weight end in failure, and two-thirds of people on diets subsequently gain more weight than they lose.
Armed with statistics, Hobbes goes on to describe the lifestyles and traumas of overweight people. The personal meets the systemic here, with faculties teaching future doctors, for example, devoting only 19 hours of their entire studies to nutrition. Which at a time when 60 process calories that Americans take in come from ultra-processed food - that is, overly processed food.
How obesity is stigmatized is again illustrated by reports from doctors' offices, where overweight people typically experience shorter appointments, are treated with less empathy by doctors, and are considered more problematic patients.
But obesity is far from just an American problem, as Hobbes writes, Since 1980, obesity rates have doubled in 73 countries and increased in 113. And in that time, no country has been able to reduce or stop the increase. Absolutely none.
