The Děčín zoo is delighted with a small macaque
"Our troop currently has seven members. Its youngest member was born on 17 August, given birth by the female Buffy and is her fifth cub, the father is the male Hitam. For the first few days after giving birth, the female carried the cub tightly pressed against her body and for a long time did not want to show the world whether she had given birth to a male or a female. However, at about three weeks of age, she gradually started to put the cub down for a little while and the keepers have known for a few days that it is a male," said zoo spokeswoman Alena Houšková, adding that the Děčín zoo has successfully raised 12 cubs of this species.
The macaques are so-called endemics of the island of Sulawesi, which means that they do not live anywhere else in the world in the wild. Their typical features are their black fur and the chocholka on their head, which gives them their name. Macaques live in rainforests, especially at lower altitudes.
Like most primates, they eat both plant and animal food. Their diet is dominated by the fruits of rainforest trees, supplemented by flowers and leaves. They meet their protein requirements by eating small arthropods, larvae and, to a lesser extent, bird eggs and chicks.
"Leaving aside the natural enemies, which are pythons, everything else is man's fault. Locals hunt macaques as a favourite prey with tasty meat and for their fur. The burning and cutting of the rainforest is also fatal to these animals," the spokesperson added.
