No Czechs or children allowed. The CTIA has uncovered discrimination in restaurants
These included misinformation about prices and failure to comply with the principles of fairness in sales.
In one case of discrimination, a restaurant in Prague refused to let smaller children into the establishment. According to the CTIA, its website states that the establishment is not suitable for children under the age of eight. "When asked electronically by a consumer whether it was possible to order a table for four adults and one child aged four at that restaurant, an employee of the restaurant replied electronically that they do not accept the presence of children under eight," Fröhlich added.
In the second case, another Prague establishment refused to allow Czech speakers to sit at the table, while allowing English speakers to do so. "The Czech-speaking inspectors, in their capacity as consumers, were not allowed to sit down at the restaurant and place an order. English-speaking consumers were allowed to do so," a spokesman for the CTIA described the situation.
Both cases are now being dealt with in administrative proceedings. As the cases have not yet been definitively closed, the spokesman could not provide further information on the restaurants in question.
However, discrimination was found only in a very small part of the restaurants inspected in the second quarter. In total, the CTIA carried out 139 inspections. In addition to the two cases of discrimination mentioned above, it found other irregularities in 64 cases. Most of these were failures to comply with the principles of fairness in sales and to inform consumers about the prices of products and services in accordance with the regulations.
Already on Wednesday, the Inspectorate reported on cases of discrimination against foreigners in two Prague restaurants, Clock Caffé and Café Restaurant. In both establishments, foreigners were charged higher amounts than Czech-speaking clients. Fines of CZK 60,000 have already become final in these cases.
