The library commemorates the anniversary of the death of Wenceslas IV with an exhibition of manuscripts
Six rare historical manuscripts from the turn of the 14th and 15th centuries, i.e. from the time of the Roman and Czech king Wenceslas IV, can be viewed today and Saturday in Prague's Klementinum. The National Library has released them from its vaults to commemorate the 600th anniversary of Wenceslas' death. This morning, librarians and restorers placed the rare originals in display cases in the Mirror Chapel. Admission to the exhibition is free, open both days from 10am to 6pm.
The exhibition of documents entitled Ad mandatum domini Regis: From the Royal Office and Library of Wenceslas IV was prepared by the library together with the National Archives. The National Archive looks at the written heritage from the reign of Václav IV from the perspective of official documents and the National Library from the perspective of literary works, said Jan Vojtíšek, the author of the exhibition.
"Visitors can look forward, for example, to a work on agriculture by Peter de Crescentiis, which is essentially a kind of encyclopaedia of agriculture, or to a breviary, i.e. the prayer book of one of the Benedictine nuns of the St George's Monastery at Prague Castle, dating from the early 15th century," he said, listing the reasons why people should see the exhibition.
Also on display will be the Epistles of Peter of Blois, where the opening miniature H (enrico) depicts the semi-detached figure of King Henry II of England. The author of the decoration is most likely the Master of Samson's History, who, in addition to the two volumes of the Bible of Wenceslaus IV, also contributed to the decoration of a number of other manuscripts. Visitors will also see John Wycliffe's Latin collection of treatises from about 1411 to 1414.
Not a single book from the library of Wenceslaus IV has survived on Czech territory. According to experts, this library was one of the most extensive and also the most beautiful book collections in Central Europe at the time, because the young king longed to build a representative library to match the book collections of his French relatives. The library, however, disappeared soon after Wenceslas' death. Apparently, it was stolen or destroyed during the Hussite conquest of the castle. A few codices were saved, however. Most of them are now owned by the Austrian National Library.
"We have a number of treasures in our collections and I am glad that they are in a condition that allows them to be displayed and made available to the public, so to speak, live and not only in the form of the digital library Manuscriptorium," said Martin Kocanda, director of the National Library.
On the day of Saturday's national holiday, a free exhibition entitled What Lies Beneath the Floor, which presents local archaeological discoveries, will also be open in Klementinum.
