Costa Rica is a champion in the fight against climate change
Costa Rica received the title for several reasons. For starters, for its plan to be carbon neutral by 2050 - something many countries have committed to under the Paris Agreement, however. The Central American nation, with a population of around five million, produces only 0.4 percent of the world's emissions. Costa Rica has also pledged to switch fully to renewable energy by 2030, with 70 percent of its buses or taxis running on electricity.
The official tourism organization says that roughly 95 percent of its energy already comes from renewable sources - in 2017, Costa Rica ran on them for a total of 300 days.
Costa Rica boasts nearly 30 national parks.
The density of forestation also contributes to reduced emissions. The rainforests with their diverse flora and fauna, which cover more than half of the country, are also one of the main tourist draws. "Costa Rica is a pioneer in conservation and sets an example for other countries in the region, as well as around the world. Climate change requires urgent action from all of us," the UN said in a statement.
Costa Rica boasts nearly 30 national parks, which is a lot considering the country's small size (51,100 square kilometers). Rain or mist forests, coral reefs or mangrove swamps are home to five percent of the world's biodiversity. The country also has volcanoes, pristine waterfalls and you would also find several rescue stations for sloths.
