Pumpkin World opening delayed by ripening pumpkins
Nová Ves u Leštiny (Havlickobrod Region) - The farm in Nová Ves u Leštiny in the Havlickobrod Region opened the Pumpkin World today for more than a month. The decorations made of thousands of freshly harvested pumpkins are dominated by massive orange pyramids in the garden. The autumn event, which is becoming a tradition, starts a week later this year because the pumpkins in the surrounding seven hectares of the Pipek family's fields took longer to ripen. There are still a lot of them in the field, Jaroslava Pipková told ČTK today.
The Pipkas grow many types of pumpkins, but the weather has been against them for the last two years. This year's harvest was delayed and some varieties did not come out. "We have enough orange pumpkins for Halloween as usual, but some of the gourmet varieties have failed," Pipková said. Still, there are several varieties to choose from at the farm, from the aforementioned large pumpkins suitable for carving and carving decorations to hokkaido cooking pumpkins or elongated "spaghetti" pumpkins to decorative gourds of various colours and shapes.
Growing pumpkins is laborious. Farmers hand hoe the plants and harvest their fruit, cutting the stem of the pumpkin with scissors. The Pipkas have been opening the Pumpkin World regularly since 2010, and past editions have attracted thousands of people. Pumpkin decorations are complemented by straw attractions or log mazes. Visitors can also see the animals raised on the farm. It will be open daily until 3 November.
Details of the event are on the farm's website, where the growers also offer some recipes for pumpkin dishes, such as pumpkin muffins or juice. Visitors tell them about other ways to adapt pumpkin in the kitchen. "A lot of cooks have tried their recipes, and we get inspired too," Pipkova said. She noted that some housewives also pickle pumpkins like cucumbers.
