Diana was exceptional in that she could grab people by the heart. In January 1997, she caused a stir when she visited Africa and, in particular, a minefield. Images of her wearing a protective suit and face shield became iconic. And even then, no one could have guessed that a few months later, the princess of human hearts would breathe her last in a tragic car crash in Paris.
Now, her younger son Harry has scored as well, as he sets off to the same place as her for the first time in 22 years. He went to a mine clearance site in Dirico, Angola, also wearing a special protective suit and looking very thoughtful. He certainly could not help thinking of his beloved mother, whom he had lost when he was only 13 years old.
Harry gave an on-the-spot speech praising the efforts of the Halo Trust, which works to defuse minefields and other explosives in countries where war has taken place. "Minefields are the unhealed wounds of war. By clearing them, we can help the community find peace, and with peace comes opportunity," he said, also calling for the preservation and conservation of wildlife and local rivers as a source of water. After this visit, the Duke of Sussex moved to Huambo to rename the local orthopaedic centre after his famous mother, Princess Diana.
He didn't forget to mention it on his official instagram account: 'The Duke is honoured to visit the place and community that were so important to his mother, to learn about their tireless mission and to speak out for all those who (Diana) felt most needed to be heard, even if the issue wasn't exactly a worldwide one,' appeared the Sussex Royal's instagram post.
