Scientists look for toddlers with a birth defect called ankle valgus in their study
Valgusity (misalignment) of the ankles is a birth defect that affects five to 10 percent of children. It is standardly treated with intensive exercise. Scientists are trying to help these children even more, so they have developed special shoes that should speed up treatment considerably.
"We have two prototypes of the shoes, which will be worn by healthy children and children with the diagnosis, to map the effect in both groups. At the same time, participation in the research will have no risks for the children and the measurements will be completely painless," explains Marta Gimunova, head of the research from the Faculty of Sports Studies at MU.
Parents of both groups of children can apply for the study via the website, where a registration form and all information is available.
The researchers are looking for fifty children with the diagnosis and fifty healthy children. Of each group, half will always wear medical shoes and half will not.
"The point at which parents should sign their child up is when they take their first independent steps, typically letting go of, for example, furniture that they are holding on to when trying to walk. Taking part in the research involves three measurements over the course of seven months from the child's first steps, each lasting about 20 minutes, and for half of the participants, it also involves wearing the shoes being tested," Gimun points out.
