Jan Šindelář's comment: Run the railways like a company
Sky's election, while apparently not entirely smooth, is the culmination of a sad tale of the state's inability to give the railways a clear direction. The board has been incomplete for over a year and even after Wednesday night that hasn't changed, as one of the members has resigned. The standstill continues.
The selection process itself was a farce from the start, if only because the requirements for candidates, especially in terms of experience, were significantly relaxed. Compared to last year's selection, the requirements for the size of the company in which the candidate had worked in the past were reduced. First the members of the selection committee and then the supervisory board played only the role of pimps.
Nebeský submitted probably the weakest professional CV of the five finalists, yet without experience from a large company he beat out experienced fighters from the management of logistics giants and transport companies. It was the participation of interesting managers from the private sector that was probably the brightest aspect (and the best hope) of the whole process. Today, those involved know that they played only the role of stage sets in a political game.
Perhaps Nebeský will surprise, show great talent and eventually emerge as the best rail boss ever. At least in the beginning, however, he will be accompanied by the aftertaste of political embarrassment. The Czech Railways will not face an easy period, they have to cope with competition in the liberalisation of the market and with a shortage of staff in operations. There is a shortage of drivers, shunters and mechanics. How can they be motivated to continue working and respect the management if the state behaves like an elephant in the china shop in the top management?
The second important group is the creditors. We will see how they interpret the games at the top of the railways next spring when the railways defend their rating. What is certain is that the lenders perceive instability. The sad thing is that someone else goes to Moody's every year to defend the rating on behalf of ČD. The agency has not escaped the frequent changes in the management of ČD and the political influence on the company, and has criticised them already this summer.
The ANO movement advocates, among other things, that the state should be run like a company. For a start, it would be enough if one large state-owned company were run like a company and not like a state. Czech Railways is still one of the largest companies in the country and it would be good if it were run by the best. They have applied, but the state has snubbed them. It can certainly be argued that the post of head of the railways has always been a political matter. But then we can forgive the antics of the selection process.
