Microplastics have reached human intestines, study confirms for the first time
Scientists have confirmed years of suspicions. A team led by University of Vienna professor Philipp Schwabl has published a study that proves for the first time the presence of microplastics in human stool. Although the study is small - with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia - tiny plastic particles measuring between 50 and 500 micrometres were found in the samples of all the people studied. None of the eight subjects were vegetarians, six avoided marine fish, and all drank water from plastic bottles and food packaged in plastic.
And it would actually be a bit of a miracle if nothing was found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example for the cosmetics industry, or created by the breakdown of larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and soda; in short, everywhere on the planet. So their entry into the human digestive tract is only officially confirmed. There were roughly 20 microplastic particles per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them in them.
Of course, lay and scientific knowledge suspects that this is not good. But humanity still doesn't know how bad it is - and what effect microplastics have on "host" organisms. Small particles can reach the bloodstream or the lymphatic system and end up, for example, in the liver. "This is the first study of its kind and it confirms what we have long thought. Now that we have the first evidence of microplastics in the human body, we need to continue to investigate what exactly this means for human health," says Schwabl.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the gut can negatively affect the immune responses of the digestive system, thereby facilitating the absorption of toxic chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far, there is no known solution other than to reduce the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. But this will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will be to at least halt its steep rise. As for plastic bottles alone, experts estimate that in three years' time humanity will be using a fifth more of them than today. The current rate is a staggering one million bottles bought per minute. Some eight million tonnes of plastic end up in the seas and oceans every year. The waste threatens marine ecosystems and contaminates the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some countries have already taken restrictions and other measures; Kenya, for example, has banned plastic bags under threat of draconian penalties. The European Commission is considering small bans (the well-known straws), and the domestic Ministry of the Environment is heading in the same direction. Critics, however, argue that such measures are nice, but totally inadequate.
